    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Cost Per Mile Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Enter your annual vehicle costs for fuel, insurance, maintenance, depreciation, and any other expenses (registration, financing, parking, tolls). Then enter the total miles driven during that period. The calculator shows cost per mile, cost per kilometer, total annual cost, and a percentage breakdown of each expense category. This comprehensive view reveals the true cost of vehicle ownership.
      </p>
      <p>
        To estimate annual depreciation, subtract the expected resale value at the end of the year from the current value. For a rough estimate, use 15-20% of the vehicle's current value per year. Maintenance costs include oil changes, tires, brakes, and repairs. Other costs can include registration fees, loan interest, parking passes, and tolls.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Understanding Vehicle Cost Per Mile</h2>
      <p>
        Most drivers underestimate their true cost per mile because they only consider fuel. However, fuel typically accounts for only 20-30% of total vehicle costs. Depreciation is often the largest expense, especially for newer vehicles. Insurance, maintenance, and financing add significantly to the total. Understanding the complete cost per mile helps you make informed decisions about commuting, road trips, ride-sharing versus driving, and vehicle purchases.
      </p>

      <h3>New vs. Used Vehicle Costs</h3>
      <p>
        New vehicles have higher per-mile costs primarily due to faster depreciation. A new $35,000 car losing $7,000 in value the first year and driven 12,000 miles adds $0.58 per mile just from depreciation. A 5-year-old used car may depreciate only $2,000 per year, adding just $0.17 per mile. However, used cars may have higher maintenance costs. The sweet spot for lowest total cost per mile is often a 3-5 year old car with good reliability ratings.
      </p>

      <h3>Electric vs. Gasoline Cost Per Mile</h3>
      <p>
        Electric vehicles (EVs) typically have lower per-mile operating costs than gasoline cars. Electricity costs roughly $0.03-0.05 per mile versus $0.08-0.15 per mile for gasoline. EVs also have lower maintenance costs with no oil changes and regenerative braking reducing brake wear. However, higher purchase prices and battery replacement costs can offset these savings. Calculate the total cost per mile for both options to make the best decision for your driving habits.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How do I calculate cost per mile for my car?</h3>
      <p>
        Add up all annual vehicle costs and divide by miles driven. If costs total $8,000 and you drive 12,000 miles, the cost per mile is $0.667.
      </p>

      <h3>What is the average cost per mile for a car?</h3>
      <p>
        According to AAA, $0.60-0.80 per mile for a new car. Smaller sedans cost $0.50-0.60, trucks and SUVs $0.70-1.00. Used cars are generally lower.
      </p>

      <h3>What costs should I include?</h3>
      <p>
        Include fuel, insurance, maintenance, repairs, depreciation, financing, registration, taxes, parking, and tolls for a complete picture.
      </p>

      <h3>How does depreciation affect cost per mile?</h3>
      <p>
        Depreciation is often the largest component. A new car can lose 20-30% of value in the first year. This is why used cars have lower cost per mile overall.
      </p>

      <h3>How do I use cost per mile for IRS mileage deduction?</h3>
      <p>
        The IRS sets a standard mileage rate ($0.67 per mile for 2024). If your actual cost per mile exceeds this, itemizing actual expenses may provide a larger deduction.
      </p>

